The Force Recon Tactical Rings feature a built in level housed into the lower portion of the rear scope ring. A perfectly plumb scope and rifle are essential for the bullet to follow a true vertical line throughout the projectile's path to the target. 
These precision, long range rings offer precise mounting for your optics onto the picatinny base and will not allow the scope to move under any recoil scenario.  Magazine are about as rare as the gun itself, and a bit costly. This gun will come with three magazines.

title: For Trade:  Savage Stevens Model 200 .223cal
postcontent:
Savage Stevens model 200 in .223 caliber with BSA Contender 6-24x40 Zoom Scope.  This rifle has been a safe queen since I bought it several years ago; I have never fired this rifle and it is excellent condition.  The scope has handling marks (stuff happens, it's huge and seems to bump into everything else when taking it in and out of the safe), but they are only cosmetic. 

The Stevens has everything needed in a good bolt-action hunting rifle. First of all, it has the time-tested Savage 110 action, that is known for reliability and safety. 

The trigger is crisp, and by adjusting the trigger tension spring screw, the pull weight can be adjusted to (3) three pounds (I have not adjusted it). 

The barrel on the Model 200 is free-floated its entire length, and the barreled action is pillar bedded into the stock.

The gray synthetic stock wears a rubber buttplate and comes equipped with sling swivel studs; the combination of the black metal action and gray stock with the mounted silver colored scope makes for a really good-looking rifle.

Scarce Beretta 92G (decock only) Brigadier Elite one.  This is one of the smoothest 92s I have ever felt.  Very light double action and crisp single action.  Night sights are dead but can be easily replaced as this model has dovetailed front and rear sights.
$850
